The shroud wraps around the aluminum cooling heatsink which on my printer has the cooling fins in a vertical orientation. I used SketchUp to design the simple surround and ducting to direct air out of the bottom of the fan/heatsink and down to the front and back of the printhead for cooling the print quite well. I added a thicker 20mm thick 40x40 fan for more airflow/pressure and sealed it using aluminum tape.  
Result: airflow is actually surprisingly good and directed exactly on print extrusion area . . . and I don't need a "flying fan" attachment.

title: QU-BD OneUp/TwoUp Pulley for Gantry Counterweight

description.text: I modified lwilder's Parametric Pulley Assembly (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:571542) scad file to allow you to change the radius of the pulley, added a guide to help keep the rope in place, and modified the dimensions of the mount. What I use it for is supporting the gantry with a counterweight. Just attach the pulley to the top with double sided tape and string it up. The current size of the pulley is sufficient for allowing a rope to go over the top without rubbing against anything, but if the weight you are using is large you may want to customize this to make it larger. For a counterweight I started with a small pill bottle filled with coins, and then added large steel washers to the string. When I was printing the mount my X-axis got nudged out of alignment so I killed the print early. If you use the skate bearing pulley you can cut down on the amount of plastic this uses as well as print time.

You can specify your bolt size in the SCAD file.  If you use the STL file then use a M8 bolt and nut.  For the skate bearing pulley you'll need a 608 skate bearing.
Tape the bottom of the pulley mount to the top of the cross support to the right of the bolt on the right side.  
With the gantry all the way up tie a string to the top wooden support of the gantry.  Run the string over the top of the pulley and tie the other end to your counterweight so that it just barely hangs in the air.  
For the counterweight you'll need something small and heavy.  I initially used a pill bottle filled with coins, but then ended up adding a bunch of steel washers in addition.
The ideal weight of the counterweight is probably the amount of weight necessary to support the gantry at level with the extruder in dead center of the build plate.  Remember that the X axis extends past the build plate and attempting to support the weight of the extruder in this area is likely unnecessary.  For me gantry sag wasn't that big of a problem to begin with so using less weight seems to be working fine (although I reserve the right to change my mind later!)

description.text:
Most Da Vinci's can't print PLA, without the heat creeping up the barrel of the hotend and causing the PLA to melt prematurely and jam.   
Adding a heatsink to the top of the block, helps dissipate the heat.  
I took an old chipset heatsink form a motherboard, clipped a couple of the fins and drilled a hole in it. I took the heatsink and mounted it on top of the block so that the barrel of the hot end (which can be seen in one of the pics) can protrude through the drilled hole. I put a washer on the barrel and tightened it down with the original nut to keep everything secure Since the mod I have been able to successfully print PLA, PVA and PC-ABS  
For better cooling, you can bend the fan bracket  as shown in the pictures to help air flow over the heatsinks which are mounted on the side of the block from the factory.  
For even Better cooling put thermal paste on the top of the hot end where it contacts the block.  
I performed all of the above methods to reduce temps in the shaft of the hotend. So far I have printed for up to 12 hours in PLA with not problems. I have since fell in love with the detail and strength of PLA and do most of my prints in PLA unless heat resistance or longevity is an issue (PLA is biodegradable).  
As for the model of Marvin, Thingiverse required I added an STL to post this.

title: Webcam Mount for Printrbot Simple Metal Heated Bed

description.text:
This is a very simple mount which can be used to attach a webcam to the right front corner of a Printrbot Simple Metal with a heated bed. Watch a demo video The Logitech C535 is highly recommended:
  • It's compatible with Octoprint/Octopi running on a Raspberry Pi 2 B+.
  • It can focus on objects as close a 7cm. (Cheaper models tend to be very blurry at anything less than 40cm.)
  • It has built-in rotation and angle adjustments.
    • To test and adjust the fit before doing a full print, see the Instructions tab. You probably want to print the size test first, and then use Customizer to adjust the groove width.

I printed this part using Printrbot's default PLA *.ini file for Cura, and Hatchbox orange filament. These settings tend to result in sharp prints, but printed pieces tend to fit more tightly than usual. So you will probably need to use Customizer to get this working:
  • Begin by choosing "Size Tester" in the customizer, and see if it slides onto the corner of the bed, with a comfortable amount of friction but no bending or scratching.
  • Adjust the size of the groove using Customizer until you're happy with the fit.
  • Print the actual mount with the same settings.
    • You can attach the camera with a heavy-duty rubber band, stretched tightly. If you're using a Logitech C535 as suggested, you should be able to use the following line in /boot/octopi.txt on your Octopi machine, and reboot: camera_usb_options="-y -r 640x480 -f 10"

You can run the following commands from the Octopi command line to manually control the camera focus. # List all available camera options. v4l2-ctl -l # Disable autofocus. v4l2-ctl -c focus_auto=0 # Configure a Logitech C525 (as seen in the photo) to # focus on the center of the print bed. Increase or decrease # in increments of 5. v4l2-ctl -c focus_absolute=70 I haven't yet looked for the right place to set these up at boot time—probably rc.local would work, assuming the camera is already connected at that point.
If you want to make a more "box-style" mount, or if you want to reuse the basic corner mount, see the OpenSCAD file included with this project.

I made these brackets to add tail lights and front running lights to my Traxxas Rustler. Luckily the track area for our Saturday night drag races is well lit, but the slow down and turn around area is not, so lights are a big help in getting the car back. Even if your need is not the same as mine, it makes the Rustler look cooler. The rear bracket uses the existing four holes in the rear shock tower. Two holes will need to be drilled in the servo cover plate for the front bracket. The Led locations in the front bracket line up with the fog light decals in the front grill of the Rustler. You just drill them through and when the body is installed the front LED lights protrude through the fog light holes. After installing the rear bracket, and with the body installed, line up the tail light plate and super glue it to the rear bracket. I used 5mm LED's from Radio Shack for the lights and servo mounting screws to mount both brackets. The LED holes and mount screw holes may need to enlarged slightly. The LED's are wired in parallel and have a 330 Ohm resistor. The resistor is a must to avoid blowing out the LED's. I use a male servo lead on both the front and rear light assemblies, and plug them into a "Y" connector, which plugs into a spare channel of the receiver. After assembly I coat all of the exposed wiring with hot glue to protect from vibration and moisture. All three files have been run through Netfabb to correct any errors. Enjoy.

description.text:
This is a Universal Charging Station (UCS) for phones that have their charging port at the bottom. It was designed for phones that accept mini USB cables but it can be used for iPhones if you find the right angled cable. It accepts a range of sizes and it’s a charging station on top of being a phone holder. The reason I designed it is that I was not satisfied with the universal phone holders on the marker for the following reasons: 1) They are mounted on the windshield glass and in Canada’s cold winter the suction cups never worked.
2) They have flexible arms that shake when driving making a simple screen touch a difficult task and plugging the charging cable in an impossible task.
3) They have foam that either interferes with the buttons or blocks the mic and the speakers. My UCS eliminates all of that: no suction cups, no shake, no foam! Adjust the UCS once to fit your phone, after that it’s easy to use: drop your phone in to hold it in place firmly, push it all the way down to charge it. The UCS not only accepts different phone sizes but it can also be mounted on different surface shapes and directions. I designed it for cars but it can also be used on desks. Good luck!

Many months later we came up with The Warthog. We modified the design to be 120 degrees. So it is between an X configuration (A Stable 90 Degrees) and an H configuration (A Sporty 180 Degrees). The original design had angled Arms which is great for racing but a little to aggressive for beginners so we took them out as well as made the arms thicker for a little more crash resistance.  
We also added Landing gears that attach to the Arms after the build is complete. Which allows you to easily change them if they break.  
We also integrated the clean plate to house a Flip32 Board.
Print the body and arms in ABS 80% Honeycomb Infill. The rest can be printed in PLA 30% Infill.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=87sbzmQVkww
Thanks to Jetty's Accelerated Firmware: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15380

  • The original 0v0 zip did not have all the needed files in it.
    The current MiZ_Rider_0v0_fixed.zip corrects this.

  • There is now 0v1 uploaded. This corrects some fiddly stuff I
    found when I assembled the thing. MiZ_Rider_0v1_No_STL.zip
    has this latest OpenSCAD code but I have not had time to generate
    the STL.
    Misery_Z_Rider_0v1_STL_ONLY.zip
    has the 8 STL build plates, ready to print.
    • MiZ is a complete Z-Stage replacement for the MakerBot Cupcake. Almost all the parts can be printed on your MakerBot. It will work with many extruders: MK5, MK6, MiseryPusher ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7129 shown) as well as any other extruder that is designed to attach to the standard MBI MK5 style extruder base plate (such as: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5684 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6713 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7113 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7037 ). The goals were to have very few modifications to the MakerBot, and to have a rigid structure that would yield good quality prints (like:
    http://www.thingiverse.com/derivative:8582 ) With my setup I can get 550mm/minute Z-travel rate:
    http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K-9MwgUz1v0 Here is a longer and more boring video:
    http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fuudemoq2MQ And yet another showing stability during a high-vibration fill:
    http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_Z8G90gfEYI Excluding nuts & bolts, re-used parts, and shipping the non-printed cost is as low as $26:
  • 2 of 12mm x 13 rods: $5 each
  • 8 of 623 bearings : $10/10 (shielded) or $20/10 (sealed)
  • ABS glue: $6
    Links to the parts are in the instructions PDF.
    • I do have some tweaks and improvements in mind. Please watch for updates. Heritage -- This design owes a lot of inspiration to these two things: Z-Rider by twotimes http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4740 Type A Z-Rider. v3.2 by TheRuttmeister http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5586 Suggestions: whosawhatsis recommended his "Minimalistic X-rod mount":
    http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6884
    instead of the version in the file. His is a nice design and should work well, it is lower profile and easier to open/close.

If you do not like waiting for Skeinforge, using your SD card for builds, going to plumbing section of the hardware store, cleaning up parts, gluing, clamping, and generally doing mechanical fiddling, this build may not be for you. But if you did not like stuff like that, why would you have a MakerBot?
There is a 15-page how to build it PDF. Please use "right-click, Save As" get it on your local disk for viewing.
The ZIP file contains the OpenSCAD files and the eight STL files need to build it. I used high resolution curves, which is overkill and will make the skeinforge process really slow. Maybe start it and go to lunch or bed or something. You will want to build from the SD card since there will be a lot of resolution in the curves.

description.text:
Ever had plenty of nylon M3 standoffs for your quadcopter builds but never the right size for your new frame?
Well here is the 1st incarnation of the Standoff Trimmer. Up to 50mm nylon standoffs
M3 bolt to align standoff
On board measurements for quick cuts Utilizes 8mm carbon rod for axle
and standard 39x19 square scraper blades. Check Instructions for printing and use

Print Main frame in a fast to Medium quality
Support is recommended but not needed if you have a Good printer, but can use support to have better shaped holes.
Print Axe with 50% infill, raft and support.- would suggest experimenting with orientation to achieve best print for blade slot.
I found laid on side with support worked fine. For axle use 8mm rod (i had some carbon spare lying around)
you may need to glue this in place once assembled. With AXE - clean out any support from blade slot and slide in blade (watch out they are sharp)
file out axle hole so that it is snug on axle but moves smoothly. blade should be parallel with bench when down.
Screw M3 bolt in side hole - not to long - approx 5 mm protruding out.
This is used to screw the standoff onto so it wont move.
Slide AXE to the desired length and place onto the standoff, with a firm hit from a heavy object like small hammer. it should part the standoff at the desired length. Unscrew the adjusted standoff. this is an unfinished project - it may require some tweeks
It some times cut on a slight angle - but easily fixed with a bit of a file.
